A tool for comparing different pseudo-random number generators (PRNG).
And a PRNG that I designed for GPU / shaders.

The generators are:
flt: RandFloat() - my PRNG that returns 1 float, range [0..1]
v2x, v2y: RandVec2() - my PRNG that returns 2 floats, range [0..1]
v3x, v3y, v3z: RandVec3() - my PRNG that returns 3 floats, range [0..1]
xor: "xor shift" PRNG  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xorshift
iq: Inigo's Integer Hash, adapted for this shader.  https://www.shadertoy.com/view/llGSzw
LCG: A popular simple PRNG called Linear congruential generator  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_congruential_generator

I'm now suspicious of any random number generator that only
has a 32-bit state. There is no way to win. But I did my best
and this is the result.

The top visualization, labeled "Zero", is a sequence of random
numbers generated from a seed of 0. *** Watch out, some PRNGs don't
recover from having a zero state (xorshift and LCG). ***

The next visualization, "Mean x256", is supposed to visualize
bias in the random number generator. This sums samples over time
and then increases their contrast. A perfect generator would
eventually match the background color of 0.5 with enough samples.

The "Seq" visualization is a sequence of calls to the PRNG, shown
left-to-right. Some PRNGs will take some time to "spin up", and
others will fall into a bad state after taking many samples.

The "Rand" visualization is just the output of the random
number generator on some pixels. Nothing too fancy here,
but you can see patterns if it's a bad generator.

There are 2 buttons at the top. By default, the random numbers here
will use a sequential seed. That means the seed on the first image pixel
will be 0, then to the right of that, 1,2,3,4 and so on. This might not
be the ideal way to init your seed in your application, but it does
help to visualize the health of the PRNG. The "Hashed seed" button will
take that same seed, but do a single call to a PRNG on the result to
get the final seed. That is only as good as the PRNG, but then after
that, things will tend to look good.

For debugging a PRNG algorithm, there is a #define BIT_BY_BIT_DEBUG
that will visualize the randomness of each bit in your 32 bit state.

My hash function looks like it's producing random numbers, but it
actually makes very structured numbers. The top 16ish bits
look very random. It takes 2^31 iterations to repeat. If it was more
random-looking, with a 32 bit state, it would repeat much sooner. This
non-randomness should actually be good for some applications because
it takes so long to repeat. It's like:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudorandom_binary_sequence

Example:
f(x) = (x^2 + x + 1) & 0xff
When called with its own output for input, this equation will start
repeating its sequence at iteration 128, but by then
it will have generated every odd number from 1 to 255, just not in
order. The order will look slightly random, but it will never repeat
a number. As you get into higher and higher bits, where there's more
wrap-around from the x^2 being masked, things look more and more random.

It turns out that there are many ways to do this same trick, and if you
mix in some other operations, like multiplies and xors, you can get it
to look more random while still not repeating any numbers and covering
every odd number. So that's what my main hash function does. Which means
that as long as that is the only thing to change the random state, my
PRNG integer state should only repeat after 2^31 or 2 billion calls.

Hopefully that's enough for applications doing stochastic things. The
bad news is, it takes less than 100th of a second for a good GPU to
generate those 2 billion randoms using this method, so it won't take
long to repeat. Also, since the float random function masks off bits,
it will have more collisions than the integer state. You still might
have to be careful. :P

Anyway, I tried to design my random/hash functions so they'd have good
tradeoffs between performance, randomness, cycle length, bias, and
with no failures like getting stuck in a zero-state. From what I
can tell, I have found a good balance for most applications compared to
what was already out there for the GPU. Please give me feedback. :D

